entry.title: [Zucchini] Refactor BufferSource::Skip().
entry.content:
BufferSource::Skip() had two main uses:

1. Advance cursor by a known number of bytes.

2. Seek to an absolute offset of an image, e.g., via:

source = std::move(BufferSource(image).Skip(offset));

To support (2), Skip() returned ref to |*this| for chaining.



In retrospect, (2) was a kludge to get BufferSource::Seek(), which in

turn was absent because BufferView is implemented as a "shrinking range"

(2 fields) instead of a "fixed range with cursor" (3 fields).



This CL makes some simple cleanup to Skip() by doing the following:

* Restrict Skip() to (1) by changing its return type to bool to indicate

whether the skip would have exceeded bound.

* Do (2) a different way: Add new BufferSource CTOR that takes an offset

param, so the above usage becomes:

source = BufferSource(image, offset);

* Down-cast BufferSource CTOR that takes ConstBufferView: Change to take

const ref instead of value, for consistency.

* Update callers.

* Update BufferSourceTest.Skip and other tests that use Skip().

* Add BufferSourceTest.{CtorWithOffset, SkipAcrossEnd}.

entry.title: Fix leak of SyncTokens during texture based VideoFrame rendering.
entry.content:
We receive multiple viz::ReleaseCallbacks for each plane in a frame

even though the frame only has a single release SyncToken. The

multiple calls cause us to issue a wait w/o a generate which leads

to SyncTokens piling up in the CommandBufferProxyImpl indefinitely.



This extracts the logic for the SyncTokenClient needed for resource

returns into a new ResourceSyncTokenClient and adds appropriate tests.



Some debugging CHECKs are also added to the CopyHardwarePlane() path

to ensure it's only being used on Android with single-texture frames.

entry.title: [text-wrap-pretty] Support block-in-inline
entry.content:
This patch supports block-in-inline for `text-wrap: pretty`.



Due to an performance optimization in `HandleBlockInInline`,

`NGLineBreaker` needs the same `NGExclusionSpace` as the one

in the `constraint_space_`. This patch adds it to the

`NGScoreLineBreaker` constructor.



`NGScoreLineBreaker` computes the line breaking by splitting

the block to 3 parts; before the block-in-inline, the block-

in-inline itself, and after, as if the 3 parts are separate

paragraphs. The unit tests cover this state transitions.

entry.title: saved_desks: Fix excessive repainting in the library
entry.content:
This CL fixes excessive repainting in the saved desk library. Prior to

this CL, just moving the cursor around in the saved desk library would

cause the entire library to be repainted.



If the cursor is moved to hover over a saved desk item, we fade in the

button to launch the template. It is positioned in the same spot as the

icons for the saved desk, so those fade out. In the old implementation,

once the icons had faded out, we would call SetVisibility on the icon

container view. This in turn triggered the containing flex layout, which

eventually results in a lot of stuff getting laid out again, which then

ends up re-painting things.



This change makes it so that the two views (the icon container and the

hover container) are always "visible". We instead modify the opacity on

the containers as needed to hide and show them. With this change in

place, no `Layout` calls happen when moving the cursor around.



BUG=b:281880456

entry.title: libassistan-v2: Temporary fix speaker id enrollment
entry.content:
In LibAssistant V2, the `kProcessState` is not received by the gRPC

client. As a temporary fix, we can use `kRecognizeState` to indicate

that the utterance is recognized and will be collected. During my tests,

the `kRecognizeState` is always followed by `kProcessState`, but cannot

rule out the possibility the utterance is not collected. But I think it

is reasonable to use `kRecognizeState` as a backup.

We will continue investigating why the `kProcessState` is not sent to

the client in b/284987346.

entry.title: [gpu] Enable GpuCleanupInBackground by default
entry.content:
It saves ~100MiB of memory on Android Vulkan devices while in background

(and sometimes even more), without any negative impact anywhere

else. Enable it by default.



For details, see the linked bug, the design doc

(https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JnlFS1GcsXAk9_N80G1su89w_Vu_yvJHovRPIwO5zWU/edit#heading=h.3wqzazt68zyb,

google internal), and results from the stable experiment. For instance

see

https://uma.googleplex.com/p/chrome/variations?sid=195b65285cab908d2d1a725bc9c64b91 (screenshot: https://screenshot.googleplex.com/7saku44ip7raLvn)

for the memory savings on Vulkan devices. There is an increase in

crashes, which is crbug.com/1444497, that has been fixed.

entry.title: [Sharesheet] Use "Copy without link" for highlight test sharing
entry.content:
Change the mechanism for highlight text sharing with generated links. With this change we can remove the #getModifyShareAction API from ChromeCustomAction.Provider.



Before:

Share sheet provides a modify action. When user decides to share without link, the share sheet will re-trigger without the generated link.



After:

Share sheet always show generated link with text sharing, while adding the origin when sharing the text title. Adding an action of "Copy without link" so user can share the text without the generated link.
